{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538301","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538301"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16156"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16156"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.13,0.01,0.63,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64159"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8847"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1786"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4655"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21088"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44690"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64159"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of painless lumps in her genital area. She has recently started a new sexual relationship. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications except for the combined oral contraceptive pill. She has no fever, itch, or discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are multiple 2-4 mm flesh-coloured, dome-shaped papules that are not hyperkeratotic and appear to collapse in the centre. There is no surrounding erythema and on lancing one of the lesions, no fluid is expelled.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Human papillomavirus infection","Genital herpes simplex virus","Scabies","Molluscum contagiosum","Folliculitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation is classic for molluscum contagiosum, with multiple small, dome-shaped papules with central umbilication. In adults, genital \u003Cstrong\u003Emolluscum contagiosum\u003C/strong\u003E is typically sexually transmitted and caused by a poxvirus. The lesions are characteristically painless and non-pruritic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenital herpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with painful vesicles that rupture to form shallow ulcers within a few days. The patient often experiences prodromal symptoms such as tingling or burning. The absence of pain, vesicles, or ulceration makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman papillomavirus infection\u003C/strong\u003E causes genital warts, which appear as flesh-coloured papules but typically have a rough, cauliflower-like surface rather than the smooth, dome-shaped appearance with central umbilication seen in molluscum contagiosum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFolliculitis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as erythematous papules or pustules centred on hair follicles. The lesions are often tender and may be pruritic. The absence of inflammation and the characteristic umbilication make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes intense pruritus, especially at night, with burrows visible in the finger webs and other characteristic locations. The absence of itch and the morphology of the lesions make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of molluscum contagiosum includes counselling about sexual transmission, and either watchful waiting (as lesions are self-limiting within 6-12 months) or active treatment with cryotherapy or curettage if lesions are extensive or causing psychological distress. Sexual partners should be informed and examined.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Molluscum contagiosum presents as small, pearly, dome-shaped papules with central umbilication.","Genital molluscum contagiosum can be sexually transmitted and requires counselling about transmission.","Treatment options include observation, cryotherapy, or curettage for extensive lesions."],"references":["Edwards S, Boffa MJ, Janier M, Calzavara-Pinton P, Rovati C, Salavastru CM, Rongioletti F, Wollenberg A, Butacu AI, Skerlev M, Tiplica GS. 2020 European guideline on the management of genital molluscum contagiosum. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol. 2021 Jan;35(1):17-26. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32881110/","Molluscum contagiosum treatment guidelines [Internet]. Mshc.org.au. 2021. Available at: https://www.mshc.org.au/health-professionals/treatment-guidelines/molluscum-contagiosum-treatment-guidelines"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16156"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49591"},"attributes":{"cre